Here at Heap Art, we are trying to inspire people to connect with each other through origami and paper folding.

In this video I will show you how to fold my modified version of the the Silvana's Star Ball unit and show you how to assemble it.

Silvana's Star Ball is a model composed of 30 modular units. Yes, it is modular origami. It is also known as a Kusudama Ball. I had some difficulty making a small version of the ball because the units do not want to stay together. This is why I modified the modular unit to have pockets for the connection. The pockets allowed me to make a small version of Silvana's Star Ball without using any glue or paperclips.

I hope you like it. Thanks for watching.

Video List.Video title: Why You Should Learn Origami!
Video List.Description:
Why you should learn origami. Origami is a form of communication. You could use it to connect to yourself or someone else. When you learn origami for yourself you are asking yourself to be a better person and to improve your skills. When you give origami as a gift, you are telling that person that you appreciate them and are happy they are in your life. The best thing about origami is when you teach origami. When you teach someone you are telling them you want to spend time with them, to befriend them and connect at a deeper level.

Video List.Video title: Moderato Origami - An Origami Ninja Moon Star ( Senban Shuriken )
Video List.Description:
In this video, learn how to fold an origami Ninja Moon Star also known as the Senban Shuriken or the Square Shape Ninja Star. I will be making one for left hand throwing and one for right hand throwing. The difference is in the spin of the ninja star when you throw it. In the video, the orange paper is for right hand throwing and the yellow paper is for left hand throwing.

I learned how to fold this ninja star when I was 8 or 9 years old. My parents owned a store in a shopping mall and the store in front of ours had a son whom was around 5 years older than me. One day he asked me if I knew how to fold a ninja star and I said yes. Then I folded a ninja star with 4 spikes, the one we all know and love. Afterward he said he would show me how to fold a different one and taught me how to fold this one, a square shape ninja star.

This is a special ninja star that throws really well and really simple to fold. However, I don't see anyone posting instructions on how to fold this ninja star on the internet.

If you have seen this origami ninja star before, Please leave a note in the comments on where you've seen it before. 

Thanks for watching.

Video List.Video title: Moderato Origami - An Origami Ninja Star ( Shuriken )
Video List.Description:
In this video we will learn how to fold an Origami Ninja Star also called a Shuriken. I learned how to fold this ninja star in summer camp. I was around 9 or 20, I do not remember how old I was during that time. During summer camp, there were volunteers who were 5 to 10 years older than us and they would take us to different parts of the city to attend different events or just to visit the local theme park. It was mainly to do some activities that are outdoors to enjoy the sun at the time. Our main mode of transport is the metro system in our city. if you are not familiar with the term metro system, It's just another way of saying the "subway" in other parts of the world. At that time our metro system had these machines that would dispense tickets we to use as transfers to us the bus systems. All of us in the summer camp would take several of these tickets to make this ninja stars on the way to our destination, including the volunteers. The tickets were made of the same type of paper as news paper so the ninja stars were not rigid enough to throw, but we did you them as book marks.

Thanks for watching.
